            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I was able to produce a similar error using the steps in the OP, though I had to time it precisely.\n\n```\nError executing vim.schedule lua callback: /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/uri.lua:82: Invalid buffer id: 1\nstack traceback:\n        [C]: in function 'nvim_buf_get_name'\n        /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/uri.lua:82: in function 'uri_from_bufnr'\n        /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/util.lua:212: in function 'get_lines'\n        /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/util.lua:275: in function 'get_line'\n        /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/util.lua:289: in function 'get_line_byte_from_position'\n        /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/util.lua:1636: in function 'buf_highlight_references'\n        /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/handlers.lua:468: in function 'handler'\n        /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/client.lua:681: in function ''\n        vim/_editor.lua: in function <vim/_editor.lua:0>\n```\n\nI think the problem is that all the async handlers don't check if the buffer is still valid. This will be in a bunch of places. We may be able to fix this centrally in `client.request`.",
